I'm Neil.

5
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Beth.

6
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
We all know how horrible it feels to be thirsty.

7
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Human bodies need around 3 litres of water a day,

8
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
and thankfully, most of us can just turn on the kitchen tap

9
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.000
to get clean drinking water.

10
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
But globally, over 2 billion people around a quarter of the world's population

11
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:37.000
live in water-stressed countries where access to water for drinking,

12
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:40.000
cooking and washing is not guaranteed.

13
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
What's more, water is also needed to grow food,

14
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:48.000
and that's getting harder due to droughts, which are increasing with climate change.

15
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
In this program, we'll visit farmers in one of the driest places on earth.

16
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.000
In the USA, where a new technology involving liquid clay

17
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:01.000
is helping farmers grow fruit and vegetables in the desert.

18
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary too.

19
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
But first, I have a question for you, Neil.

20
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Everyone knows that plants need sunlight and water to grow,

21
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.000
but soil is just as important.

22
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
One of the most useful soils is clay.

23
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.000
A dense, smooth soil, which is very fertile, but sticky.

24
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Clay has been used in agriculture for thousands of years,

25
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
but what is its more modern use?

26
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Is clay good for a, curing headaches,

27
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.000
b, digesting food, or c, smoothing face skin?

28
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Well, I think clay can be used to smooth the skin on people's faces.

29
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
OK, Neil, we'll find out if that's the correct answer later.

30
00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Like a water and farming are closely connected.

31
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Agriculture uses a massive 70% of the world's fresh water supply,

32
00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
so ways to use water more efficiently are much needed.

33
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Oles Sivotsen's company does it control, works with date farmers in Yuma,

34
00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.000
an area on the border of California and Mexico.

35
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
One of the hottest places on earth,

36
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:17.000
Yuma has been experiencing its worst drought in 500 years,

37
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:22.000
forcing farmers to pump water from rivers to grow their date palm trees.

38
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Fortunately, Oles team have created a liquid that they say

39
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
can turn the sandy desert soil into a sponge,

40
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
which holds water and nutrients.

41
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Here, he explains his invention to Anthony Wallace,

42
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
reporter for BBC World Service Program, People Fixing the World.

43
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
To understand how it works, we need to look at the difference between sandy soil

44
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.000
and clay soil.

45
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:47.000
Sandy desert soil has a lot of gaps in it,

46
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.000
so water drains through it quickly,

47
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.000
making it harder for plants to establish a root system in the ground.

48
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
But clay soil is made up of much smaller particles that cling together

49
00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
and naturally stop water from escaping.

50
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
It creates the habitat for the soil microbiology

51
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
to also start to develop any bowl.

52
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Kind of a kickstart as well to nature's natural processes.

53
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
The problem with sandy soil is that it drains water.

54
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
If you drain something, you remove the liquid from it.

55
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Clay soil, on the other hand, is made of smaller particles,

56
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
which cling or stick together tightly and hold water,

57
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:26.000
helping plants grow.

58
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.000
Oles makes a liquid by mixing clay and water,

59
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
which changes the soil composition and kick starts the growth of his trees.

60
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
The liquid makes the trees start growing more quickly.

61
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Liquid clay technology is still new,

62
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
and costing around $2,000 an acre, it's not cheap.

63
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:49.000
But Ole claims his technique halves the amount of water needed to grow fruit trees,

64
00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
and that most farmers will make back their investment within two years.

65
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Oles claims sound too good to be true,

66
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
but other downsides to interfering with nature in this way.

67
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Presenters, Myra and Nubi, and Anthony Wallace discuss this question

68
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
for BBC World Services people fixing the world.

69
00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.000
Anthony, I'm still left wondering,

70
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.000
right when you manipulate soil like this,

71
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
could you be causing problems down the line?

72
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
Yeah, I think anytime that there's a new technology where you are,

73
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
like you said, manipulating nature,

74
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:26.000
only time will tell what the long-term effects of that will be.

75
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.000
But Ole did stress that their liquid clay

76
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:34.000
does not use any chemicals, only clay, air, and water.

77
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Oles liquid clay involves manipulating soil,

78
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:41.000
using and controlling it skillfully to achieve some results.

79
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Myra worries that when people do this,

80
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
they could create problems down the line,

81
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
at some unspecified point in the future.

82
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:54.000
In fact, only time will tell if liquid clay is a long-term solution

83
00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.000
to the problem of water scarcity.

84
00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.000
The phrase only time will tell means that the result of something happening now

85
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.000
will not be known until the future.

86
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Something we can know, though, is the answer to my question, Neil.

87
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Yes, you asked about a modern use for clay,

88
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
and I guessed it was for smoothing facial skin.

89
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Which was the correct answer.

90
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
A clay mask, also called a mud pack,

91
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.000
is used to smooth the skin on your face.

92
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
OK, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program,

93
00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
starting with the verb to drain, which means to remove liquid.

94
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
To cling, it means to stick or hold tightly onto something.

95
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:40.000
If you kick start something, you make it start or develop more quickly.

96
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
To manipulate means to skillfully use or control something.

97
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
The phrase down the line means some time in the future.

98
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And finally, the idiom only time will tell means that the truth about something happening now

99
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:55.000
will only be known in the future.

100
00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:59.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember to join us again next time

101
00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:03.000
for more trending topics and useful vocabulary here at six minute English.

102
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Goodbye for now.

103
